<div id="post6" class="post-content" style="display:none">
  <span class="post-tag">Lawn Care & Turf Management</span>
  <h2 class="post-title">Saint Augustine Grass Fungus in Tampa Bay: Prevention & Treatment Guide for South Tampa Homeowners</h2>
  <p class="post-meta">March 15, 2026 &nbsp;·&nbsp; Written by Dan Letbetter, Owner — Water Oak Irrigation</p>

  <p>If you're a South Tampa homeowner, you've probably seen it: those brown, dead patches spreading across your Saint Augustine lawn, despite regular watering and care. That's fungus—and it's one of the most damaging threats to Florida lawns.</p>

  <p>Saint Augustine grass is the dominant turf type in South Tampa, Hyde Park, Davis Island, and throughout the Tampa Bay area. It's drought-tolerant, handles our sandy soil well, and provides that lush, carpet-like appearance that makes Tampa properties beautiful. But Saint Augustine's dense growth also makes it the perfect environment for fungal diseases that thrive in humidity and heat.</p>

  <p>In this comprehensive guide, we'll explain exactly what's killing your Saint Augustine lawn, how to prevent fungal outbreaks, and when to call a professional for turf management treatment.</p>

  <h3>Why Saint Augustine Grass Gets Fungus (Tampa Bay's Perfect Storm)</h3>
  <p>Tampa's climate is literally ideal for fungal disease development. Understanding why fungus thrives here helps you prevent it:</p>

  <h4>High Humidity + Warm Temperatures</h4>
  <p>Florida's subtropical climate provides the exact conditions fungi need. Temperature between 70-85°F and humidity above 70% create a fungal breeding ground. During Tampa's summer months (June-September), we rarely see conditions below these thresholds.</p>

  <h4>Night-Time Leaf Wetness</h4>
  <p>Dew, irrigation overspray, or rainfall leaves Saint Augustine grass blades wet overnight. Fungal spores need 6-8 hours of leaf wetness to germinate and infect grass. In Tampa, this happens almost every night during warm months.</p>

  <h4>Sandy Soil = Poor Water Drainage</h4>
  <p>Tampa's sandy soil drains quickly, which is good for preventing root rot, but it also means it dries out fast. When homeowners irrigate to keep their lawns green, they often over-water, creating the humid, wet conditions fungi love. If your irrigation isn't properly adjusted for Florida, you're actually feeding the fungus.</p>

  <h4>Thatch Buildup in Dense Saint Augustine</h4>
  <p>Saint Augustine naturally accumulates thatch (dead grass tissue that builds up at the soil surface). Thatch creates a wet, humid microclimate at the grass base—the perfect incubator for fungal spores.</p>

  <h4>Poor Lawn Maintenance</h4>
  <p>If your lawn isn't regularly aerated, fertilized correctly, or mowed at the proper height, it becomes weak and susceptible to fungal invasion. A healthy, vigorous Saint Augustine lawn resists fungal disease better than a struggling one.</p>

  <h3>Common Fungal Diseases Destroying South Tampa Lawns</h3>

  <h4>1. Brown Patch (Rhizoctonia solani)</h4>
  <p><strong>What it looks like:</strong> Large, circular patches of brown or tan grass, often with a darker border and a lighter center. Patches can grow rapidly—sometimes expanding a foot or more per day during active disease.</p>

  <p><strong>When it strikes:</strong> Brown patch is worst in late spring (April-May) and fall (September-October) when temperatures are warm but not scorching. It's less active during peak summer heat.</p>

  <p><strong>Why Saint Augustine is vulnerable:</strong> Saint Augustine's dense growth and high thatch layer make it extremely susceptible. Brown patch starts at the soil surface and works upward, so the thicker your thatch, the worse the infection.</p>

  <p><strong>Real-world example:</strong> We recently treated a South Tampa property in Hyde Park where brown patch spread across 40% of the lawn in just 3 weeks. The homeowner had switched to daily irrigation during a hot spell, creating perfect fungal conditions. After treatment and irrigation adjustment, the lawn recovered completely.</p>

  <h4>2. Dollar Spot (Sclerotinia homoeocarpa)</h4>
  <p><strong>What it looks like:</strong> Silver dollar-sized (or smaller) spots of tan or straw-colored dead grass. Unlike brown patch, dollar spot patches are much smaller and more numerous, creating a mottled appearance across the lawn.</p>

  <p><strong>When it strikes:</strong> Dollar spot is active year-round in Florida, but worst during warm, humid spring and fall months. It also thrives on nutrient-poor lawns, so it's often a sign of fertilization problems.</p>

  <p><strong>Why Saint Augustine is vulnerable:</strong> Dollar spot loves dense turf and is very common on Saint Augustine, especially if the grass is under-fertilized or stressed.</p>

  <h4>3. Leaf Spot and Melting Out (Drechslera, Bipolaris, Curvularia)</h4>
  <p><strong>What it looks like:</strong> Dark brown or purple spots on grass blades, often with yellow halos. As the disease progresses, blades wither and the grass thins, eventually leading to bare patches.</p>

  <p><strong>When it strikes:</strong> This complex of fungi is worst during warm, wet conditions. In Tampa, it's active spring through fall.</p>

  <p><strong>Why Saint Augustine is vulnerable:</strong> Saint Augustine's broad leaf blades provide a large target for spot fungi. Wet conditions from irrigation or rain create perfect conditions for spore spread.</p>

  <h4>4. Take-All Root Rot (Gaeumannomyces graminis)</h4>
  <p><strong>What it looks like:</strong> Sudden, severe yellowing and death of large sections of grass. Unlike spot diseases, take-all affects the entire plant including roots, so affected areas don't recover on their own.</p>

  <p><strong>When it strikes:</strong> Take-all is most serious during cooler months (November-March) when root growth slows. Recovery happens faster in summer heat, which is why this disease is more damaging in Florida's mild winters.</p>

  <p><strong>Why it's dangerous:</strong> Take-all kills grass at the root level, so irrigation and fungicide won't help much. Prevention is critical. The fungus spreads through soil and can remain dormant for years.</p>

  <h3>How to Spot Fungus EARLY (Before It Destroys Your Lawn)</h3>

  <div class="post-tip">
    <strong>🔍 Early Warning Signs:</strong><br>
    <strong>Small tan spots appearing</strong> — Dollar spot or leaf spot fungus are starting. Treat immediately before they spread.<br><br>
    <strong>Circular patch of brown grass with a darker ring</strong> — Brown patch is developing. The border defines the active infection zone.<br><br>
    <strong>Grass blades have spots with yellow halos</strong> — Leaf spot fungus is present. Check if spots have the characteristic appearance.<br><br>
    <strong>Blades are dying from the tip down</strong> — Melting out or take-all root rot may be developing.<br><br>
    <strong>Sudden wilting despite adequate moisture</strong> — Root rot fungus damage (take-all or pythium) is likely.<br><br>
    <strong>White, powdery coating on blades</strong> — Powdery mildew is developing (less common in Tampa's humidity, more common in shade).<br><br>
    <strong>Musty odor in the lawn</strong> — Fungal activity is significant. Immediate action needed.
  </div>

  <h3>Preventing Fungus: The Best Treatment</h3>
  <p>Preventing fungal disease is far easier (and cheaper) than treating a severe outbreak. Here's how to keep your South Tampa lawn fungus-free:</p>

  <h4>1. Optimize Your Irrigation System (Critical!)</h4>
  <p>This is the #1 fungus prevention strategy: water your lawn correctly.</p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Water in early morning (4-7 AM)</strong> — Never in evening. Evening irrigation leaves grass wet overnight, creating fungal conditions.</li>
    <li><strong>Water deeply but less frequently</strong> — This encourages deep roots and allows the soil to dry between waterings. Shallow, frequent watering creates constant humidity.</li>
    <li><strong>Avoid afternoon heat watering</strong> — Not only is it inefficient in Tampa heat, it stresses grass and makes it susceptible to fungus.</li>
    <li><strong>Get your system optimized professionally</strong> — We can adjust your zones, run times, and schedule to provide ideal moisture without creating fungal conditions.</li>
  </ul>

  <h4>2. Proper Mowing Height and Frequency</h4>
  <p>For Saint Augustine in Tampa: Mow at 2.5-3.5 inches height, cutting no more than 1/3 of the blade length at once.</p>

  <ul>
    <li>Cutting too short (below 2 inches) stresses grass and invites fungal invasion</li>
    <li>Cutting more than 1/3 of the blade creates wounds where spores enter</li>
    <li>Keep mower blades sharp—dull blades tear grass, creating infection points</li>
    <li>Don't bag clippings in fungal-heavy periods (spores spread via equipment)</li>
  </ul>

  <h4>3. Proper Fertilization</h4>
  <p>An undernourished lawn is a fungus-prone lawn. Saint Augustine needs:</p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Spring (March-May):</strong> Moderate nitrogen fertilization to support growth</li>
    <li><strong>Summer (June-August):</strong> Reduce nitrogen (high nitrogen during heat increases fungal susceptibility)</li>
    <li><strong>Fall (September-November):</strong> Resume nitrogen to encourage growth before dormancy</li>
    <li><strong>Winter (December-February):</strong> Light fertilization or none, depending on your lawn's needs</li>
  </ul>

  <p>Over-fertilization with nitrogen makes grass succulent and attractive to fungi. Under-fertilization makes grass weak and vulnerable. Balance is critical.</p>

  <h4>4. Thatch Management</h4>
  <p>Saint Augustine naturally accumulates thatch. Every 2-3 years, have your lawn:</p>

  <ul>
    <li>Aerified — This breaks up thatch, improves drainage, and reduces fungal habitat</li>
    <li>Dethatched — Physically remove excessive dead grass tissue</li>
    <li>Power-raked — For severe thatch buildup</li>
  </ul>

  <p>Removing thatch reduces the wet, humid microclimate fungi love.</p>

  <h4>5. Improve Air Circulation</h4>
  <p>Fungi need moisture and stagnant air to thrive. To increase airflow:</p>

  <ul>
    <li>Prune tree branches to allow sunlight and airflow to reach grass</li>
    <li>Remove landscape debris that traps moisture</li>
    <li>Avoid dense landscape plantings that create humid microclimates near grass</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>When DIY Prevention Isn't Enough: Professional Treatment</h3>
  <p>If you've followed prevention steps and fungus still appears, it's time for professional turf management treatment.</p>

  <h4>Fungicide Treatment Options</h4>
  <p><strong>Preventive fungicides:</strong> Applied before fungal disease develops, during high-risk periods (spring and fall). These are cheaper and more effective than treating established fungus.</p>

  <p><strong>Curative fungicides:</strong> Applied when fungus is actively spreading. These are more expensive and less reliable than prevention, but necessary when disease is present.</p>

  <p><strong>Biological fungicides:</strong> Safer for the environment and pets, but often less potent than chemical options.</p>

  <p>We recommend a combination approach: preventive fungicide during high-risk seasons, plus excellent cultural practices (mowing, irrigation, aeration) year-round.</p>

  <h4>Professional Turf Management Program Benefits</h4>
  <p>At Water Oak Irrigation, our South Tampa turf management program includes:</p>

  <ul>
    <li>Regular lawn inspections (monthly during growing season)</li>
    <li>Early fungal disease detection and immediate response</li>
    <li>Irrigation system optimization to prevent fungal conditions</li>
    <li>Fertilization schedule tailored to Saint Augustine and season</li>
    <li>Thatch management and aeration when needed</li>
    <li>Professional fungicide application during high-risk periods</li>
    <li>Documentation and monitoring of results</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>South Tampa Neighborhoods We Serve</h3>
  <p>We provide professional turf management and fungal disease treatment throughout South Tampa, including:</p>

  <ul>
    <li>Hyde Park</li>
    <li>Culbreath Isles</li>
    <li>Palma Ceia</li>
    <li>Davis Island</li>
    <li>Harbour Island</li>
    <li>South Hyde Park</li>
    <li>Carver City</li>
  </ul>

  <p>If your South Tampa lawn is showing signs of fungal disease, contact us for a free evaluation and treatment recommendation.</p>

  <h3>Common Questions About Saint Augustine Fungus</h3>

  <h4>Can I use a home fungicide from the garden center?</h4>
  <p>You can, but professional-grade fungicides are more effective. Garden center products are often weaker formulations and may not be applied correctly. We recommend professional treatment for active fungal disease.</p>

  <h4>If I treat the fungus, will it come back?</h4>
  <p>If you just treat fungus without addressing the underlying conditions (irrigation, fertilization, thatch), yes, it will likely return. That's why we always address root causes alongside treatment.</p>

  <h4>Is fungicide safe for pets and kids?</h4>
  <p>Modern fungicides are relatively safe when applied properly, with a short re-entry time (usually 24 hours). We'll advise you on any precautions needed for your specific situation.</p>

  <h4>How often do I need professional fungicide treatment?</h4>
  <p>During high-risk seasons (spring and fall), a monthly preventive program is ideal. In low-risk months, prevention focuses on cultural practices (mowing, irrigation, fertilization) rather than fungicide.</p>

  <h4>Can my lawn recover from severe fungal damage?</h4>
  <p>Yes, in most cases. Saint Augustine is resilient, and once you stop the active infection and address its causes, the grass will fill in damaged areas. Severe cases (like take-all) may require reseeding, but most fungal damage recovers within weeks of treatment.</p>

