<!-- POST 9: WELL PUMP SERVICE -->
<div id="post9" class="post-content" style="display:none">
  <span class="post-tag">Equipment Service</span>
  <h2 class="post-title">Well Pump Service in Tampa Bay: Repair, Replacement & Maintenance Guide</h2>
  <p class="post-meta">March 15, 2026 &nbsp;·&nbsp; Written by Dan Letbetter, Owner — Water Oak Irrigation</p>

  <p>For Tampa Bay properties with private wells, a broken well pump means your entire irrigation system stops working. Unlike municipal water connections that continue working when problems occur, well pumps require regular maintenance and occasional professional service to prevent system failure.</p>

  <p>In this comprehensive guide, we explain how well pumps work, how to spot problems early, when to repair versus replace, and how to maintain pumps for maximum lifespan and reliability.</p>

  <h3>How Well Pump Systems Work (The Basics)</h3>

  <p>A well pump irrigation system includes three main components:</p>

  <h4>1. The Well Pump (Submersible or Jet)</h4>
  <p><strong>Submersible pumps</strong> (most common in Florida) sit at the bottom of the well and push water up. They're efficient and reliable, but repair requires pulling the entire pump from the well.</p>

  <p><strong>Jet pumps</strong> sit above ground and pull water up (shallow wells only). Less common in Florida because we have deeper wells, but easier to service.</p>

  <h4>2. Pressure Tank</h4>
  <p>Stores water under pressure so the pump doesn't need to run constantly. When you open a valve, pressurized water flows out. When pressure drops, the pump activates to refill the tank.</p>

  <h4>3. Check Valves and Backflow Prevention</h4>
  <p>Prevent water from flowing backward and protect the well pump from damage. Required by Florida code.</p>

  <h3>Signs Your Well Pump Needs Service</h3>

  <h4>Loss of Water Pressure</h4>
  <p>If your system suddenly has weak pressure in all zones, the well pump may be failing. This is different from low pressure in one zone (which usually indicates a line problem).</p>

  <h4>Pump Won't Start</h4>
  <p>The pump doesn't activate when pressure drops. Usually indicates electrical failure, but can also mean mechanical pump problems.</p>

  <h4>Pump Runs Constantly</h4>
  <p>If the pump never stops running, the pressure tank may have failed, or there may be a leak in the system causing continuous pressure loss.</p>

  <h4>Spurting or Reduced Flow</h4>
  <p>The pump may be cavitating (losing prime) due to a leak in the inlet line or a failing check valve.</p>

  <h4>Unusual Noise</h4>
  <p>Grinding, squealing, or rattling sounds indicate mechanical failure inside the pump. Don't ignore these—they signal imminent failure.</p>

  <h4>Visible Water Leaks Near the Well Head</h4>
  <p>Leaks indicate problems with check valves, fittings, or the pressure tank. Can waste water and damage the well pump.</p>

  <h3>When to Repair vs. Replace</h3>

  <h4>Repair Makes Sense If:</h4>
  <ul>
    <li>Pump is less than 10 years old</li>
    <li>Problem is a simple component (pressure switch, capacitor, check valve)</li>
    <li>Repair cost is less than 50% of replacement cost</li>
  </ul>

  <h4>Replace Makes Sense If:</h4>
  <ul>
    <li>Pump is over 15 years old</li>
    <li>Internal pump damage (bearings, seals) requiring complete rebuild</li>
    <li>Repair cost exceeds 50% of new pump cost</li>
    <li>Pump has failed multiple times (sign of age/wear)</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Well Pump Repair Services</h3>

  <h4>Electrical Repairs</h4>
  <p>Problems with capacitors, wiring, or control switches often make it seem like the pump is broken when it's really just an electrical component. These are usually inexpensive fixes.</p>

  <h4>Pressure Tank Service</h4>
  <p>Pressure tanks wear out and lose their ability to hold pressure. Often replacing the tank solves "pump won't turn off" problems.</p>

  <h4>Check Valve Replacement</h4>
  <p>Failed check valves allow water to flow backward, causing pressure loss and pump cycling issues. Replacement is straightforward and inexpensive.</p>

  <h4>Line Repair</h4>
  <p>Leaks in the inlet line (from well to pump) or discharge line (from pump to tank) reduce pump efficiency or prevent proper function. We locate and repair leaks.</p>

  <h4>Complete Pump Replacement</h4>
  <p>When internal damage makes repair uneconomical, we pull the old pump and install a new one, including pressure tank and check valve service.</p>

  <h3>Well Pump Maintenance (Prevent Problems)</h3>

  <h4>Annual Inspection</h4>
  <p>We check pressure, water quality, electrical components, and listen for unusual sounds. Early detection prevents costly failures.</p>

  <h4>Pressure Tank Service</h4>
  <p>Every 2-3 years, pressure tanks should be recharged (the air bladder loses pressure over time). This is a simple, inexpensive maintenance task.</p>

  <h4>Sediment and Mineral Removal</h4>
  <p>Tampa's well water can be high in minerals and sediment. We can install filters to protect the pump and improve water quality.</p>

  <h4>Winterization (November)</h4>
  <p>Even rare freezes can damage well pumps. Pre-freeze inspection ensures the system is protected.</p>

  <h3>Well Pump Lifespan and Replacement Cost</h4>

  <p><strong>Expected Lifespan:</strong> 15-25 years with proper maintenance. Submersible pumps in Florida wells often last 20+ years if water quality is good.</p>

  <p><strong>Replacement Cost:</strong> $2,500-$6,000 including pump, tank, installation, and testing. Price varies based on:</p>

  <ul>
    <li>Well depth (deeper wells need stronger, more expensive pumps)</li>
    <li>Flow requirements (larger systems need larger pumps)</li>
    <li>Pressure tank size</li>
    <li>Difficulty of access</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Well Water Quality and Pump Protection</h3>

  <p>Tampa Bay well water often contains iron, manganese, and sediment that can damage pumps and sprinkler heads. If you have well-drawn water:</p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Install a filter:</strong> Protects pump and downstream equipment</li>
    <li><strong>Monitor water quality:</strong> High iron can clog sprinkler heads and valves</li>
    <li><strong>Treat water if needed:</strong> For drinking/household use, but irrigation water filtration alone may suffice</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Questions About Well Pumps</h3>

  <h4>How often should well pumps be serviced?</h4>
  <p>Annual inspections are ideal. If the pump is performing well, basic maintenance every 2-3 years (pressure tank recharge) is usually sufficient.</p>

  <h4>Can I repair a well pump myself?</h4>
  <p>Submersible well pumps require special tools and expertise. DIY repair is not recommended. Professional service is safer and more reliable.</p>

  <h4>What's the difference between well pump repair and submersible pump repair?</h4>
  <p>Submersible pump repair is specialized—the pump must be pulled from the well, which requires specific equipment. We handle this expertise.</p>

  <h4>How do I know if my well water is suitable for irrigation?</h4>
  <p>We can test your water quality and recommend filtration if needed. Most Tampa well water works fine for irrigation with proper filtration.</p>

